04624nam a22005535i 9780226169910DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802261699107 a10.7208/97802261699102doi  a(DE-B1597)523349  a(OCoLC)887802772  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aR601b.L45 2014eb 7aMED0000002bisacsh04a610.9512231 aLei, Sean Hsiang-lin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNeither Donkey nor Horse :bMedicine in the Struggle over China's Modernity /cSean Hsiang-lin Lei. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b4 halftones, 1 line drawing  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- t1. Introduction -- t2. Sovereignty and the Microscope: The Containment of the Manchurian Plague, 1910-11 -- t3. Connecting Medicine with the State: From Missionary Medicine to Public Health, 1860-1928 -- t4. Imagining the Relationship between Chinese Medicine and Western Medicine, 1890-1928 -- t5. The Chinese Medical Revolution and the National Medicine Movement -- t6. Visualizing Health Care in 1930s Shanghai -- t7. Science as a Verb: Scientizing Chinese Medicine and the Rise of Mongrel Medicine -- t8. The Germ Theory and the Prehistory of "Pattern Differentiation and Treatment Determination" -- t9. Research Design as Political Strategy: The Birth of the New Antimalaria Drug Changshan -- t10. State Medicine for Rural China, 1929-49 223 -- t11. Conclusion: Thinking with Modern Chinese Medicine -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute Columbia University0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNeither Donkey nor Horse tells the story of how Chinese medicine was transformed from the antithesis of modernity in the early twentieth century into a potent symbol of and vehicle for China's exploration of its own modernity half a century later. Instead of viewing this transition as derivative of the political history of modern China, Sean Hsiang-lin Lei argues that China's medical history had a life of its own, one that at times directly influenced the ideological struggle over the meaning of China's modernity and the Chinese state. Far from being a remnant of China's premodern past, Chinese medicine in the twentieth century coevolved with Western medicine and the Nationalist state, undergoing a profound transformation-institutionally, epistemologically, and materially-that resulted in the creation of a modern Chinese medicine. This new medicine was derided as "neither donkey nor horse" because it necessarily betrayed both of the parental traditions and therefore was doomed to fail. Yet this hybrid medicine survived, through self-innovation and negotiation, thus challenging the conception of modernity that rejected the possibility of productive crossbreeding between the modern and the traditional. By exploring the production of modern Chinese medicine and China's modernity in tandem, Lei offers both a political history of medicine and a medical history of the Chinese state.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMedicinexChinaxHistory. 0aMedicinexHistoryx20th centuryxChina. 0aMedicinezChinaxHistoryy20th century. 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226169910423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226169910.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3